	<div class="history-block clear-both" zum-waypoint="waypoints" down="third.on" offset="30%">
		<div class="block-3" ng-class="{'animated fadeIn': waypoints.third.on}">
			<h2>History</h2>
			<p class="long-para">Taiwan was originally connected to China until sea levels rose around 10,000 years ago. It wasn’t until roughly 8,000 years ago that Austronesians settled in Taiwan, who are now referred to as today’s Taiwanese aborigines. Through different periods of times, the island of Taiwan had many different names from different explorers and rulers. In 1544, Portuguese sailors sighted the island and was enticed by its beauty and named Taiwan – “Ilha Formosa,” which translates to Beautiful Island. In the early 17th century, the Dutch East India Company established a commercial post at Fort Zeelandia (which is now called Anping, Tainan) on a coastal sandbar called Tayuan, which refers to foreigners. The modern word Taiwan is derived from Tayuan, which had a historic transformation from 大員, 大圓, 大灣, 臺員, 臺圓 and 臺窩灣. Tainan, one of the five largest cities located in Taiwan, was the first permanent settlement by western colonists and Chinese immigrants as the most significant trading port. Tainan was also the capital of Taiwan during that time until 1887.
			<br><br>
			During World War II, the Qing Dynasty was defeated in the First Sino-Japanese War in 1894-1895. Taiwan and Penghu were ceded in full sovereignty to the Japanese Empire. During this time, pro-Qing high officials, proclaimed as the Republic of Formosa, resisted against Japanese Rule. However, all resistance and rebellious groups were unsuccessful. Republic of China (ROC) was the official name of the state established in 1912, commonly referred to as Free China. However in 1949, the Nationalist Party, led by Chiang Kai-shek, was defeated in the Chinese Civil War by the Communist Party and fled to Taiwan with over two million people. The Japanese Rule did not end until the end of World War II on October 25th, 1945, and was not fully independent until the Treaty of San Francisco took effect in 1952. The instrument of surrender was handed to the ROC military in Taiwan.
			<br><br>
			The 228 Incident and White Terror are significant periods for Taiwan’s history, <a href="" class="btn-link">read more here</a>.
			<br><br>
			ROC was a member of the UN until 1971 when the People's Republic of China (PRC), the current China, took the seat away. Throughout the years, the name Republic of China has slowly faded and the country is more commonly referred to as Taiwan. During the Olympics, Chinese Taipei was used due to diplomatic reasons with China.</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="content-container clear-both">
